## 8. MCP Server vs WebSocket — Communication Layer

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This is a critical architectural decision.

### Current State
You currently send WebSocket requests based on form values the user selects. The question is whether the server side should expose an **MCP Server** for the LLM to call, or whether the existing WebSocket approach should be reused.

### Option 1: Keep Existing WebSocket (Recommended for Phase 1)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant Electron
    participant Proxy as LLM Proxy (Backend)
    participant Bedrock as AWS Bedrock
    participant WS as WebSocket Server

    User->>Electron: NL query
    Electron->>Proxy: NL query + TEA token
    Proxy->>Bedrock: Schema + NL query (NO trade data)
    Bedrock-->>Proxy: Query JSON
    Proxy-->>Electron: Validated query JSON
    Electron->>WS: Send query + TEA token
    WS-->>Electron: Trade results
    Electron->>Electron: Populate AG Grid
```

| Pros | Cons |
|------|------|
| **Zero server-side changes** — reuse existing WebSocket query format | LLM doesn't interact with server directly; frontend is the orchestrator |
| Fast to implement; LLM produces the same JSON your forms currently produce | Frontend must validate/sanitize LLM output before sending to server |
| Existing TEA token auth, rate limiting, and error handling work as-is | Cannot leverage MCP's tool discovery for future AI capabilities |
| **Trade data never touches the LLM** — only the generated query does | |
| Lower complexity; easier to debug | |

### Option 2: MCP Server (Better for Long-Term AI Integration)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant Frontend
    participant LLM as LLM Agent
    participant MCP as MCP Server
    participant DB as Trade DB

    User->>Frontend: NL query
    Frontend->>LLM: User query + MCP tool descriptions
    LLM->>MCP: Tool call: search_trades({filters})
    MCP->>DB: Execute query
    DB-->>MCP: Results
    MCP-->>LLM: Formatted results
    LLM-->>Frontend: Results + summary
    Frontend->>Frontend: Populate AG Grid
```

| Pros | Cons |
|------|------|
| **Standardized protocol** — any MCP-compatible LLM can discover and use your trade search tools | **Requires server-side changes** — must build an MCP server exposing trade search, trade detail, aggregation tools etc. |
| Self-describing — the LLM discovers available tools and their schemas automatically | More complex architecture to maintain |
| Future-proof — can add new tools (position lookup, risk calc) without frontend changes | MCP is still relatively new; ecosystem is maturing |
| Supports multi-step agentic workflows (search → analyze → alert) | Adds new infrastructure component (MCP server process) |
| Better separation of concerns — LLM talks to server directly | Authentication & authorization must be handled in MCP layer |

### 🏆 Recommendation

**Phase 1: Reuse WebSocket** — Get the feature working by having the LLM produce the same query format your forms generate today. Zero server changes needed.

**Phase 2: Introduce MCP Server** — Once the concept is proven, build an MCP server on top of your existing query engine. This enables richer agentic capabilities like:
- `search_trades` — search with filters
- `get_trade_details` — fetch a single trade
- `get_portfolio_summary` — aggregated view
- `get_counterparty_exposure` — risk-related queries

