## 9. Server-Side Requirements

### Minimum Requirements (Phase 1 — WebSocket Reuse)

Since the LLM output will mirror your existing form-based query format, server-side changes are minimal:

| Requirement | Details |
|-------------|---------|
| **No changes to query API** | LLM generates the same JSON format your forms produce |
| **Robust input validation** | Tighten server-side validation — LLM may generate edge-case values that forms never would (e.g., extremely large date ranges, unusual operator combinations) |
| **Rate limiting** | AI-driven searches may increase query volume; ensure rate limits are appropriate |
| **Query logging** | Log which queries came from AI vs. manual form to track accuracy and performance |
| **Error messages** | Return structured, descriptive error messages (the LLM may need to retry or explain the error to the user) |

### New Backend Requirement: LLM Proxy Service

A lightweight backend proxy is needed to securely call AWS Bedrock:

| Requirement | Details |
|-------------|---------|
| **Endpoint** | `POST /api/ai/translate-query` — accepts NL query, returns structured JSON |
| **Auth** | Validates incoming TEA token before processing |
| **Bedrock Integration** | Uses AWS SDK to call `InvokeModel` on Bedrock (Claude) |
| **Prompt Management** | Stores and versions system prompts server-side (not in frontend) |
| **Input Sanitization** | Strips any potentially injected data from user input |
| **Response Validation** | Validates LLM output against expected JSON schema before returning to frontend |
| **Audit Logging** | Logs every query: user ID, NL input, generated query, model used, latency |
| **Rate Limiting** | Per-user rate limiting to prevent abuse (e.g., 30 queries/minute) |

### API Structure Placeholder

> [!NOTE]
> Server-side API structure will be provided later. The following is a placeholder to define the contract between the LLM proxy and the frontend.

**Request** (`POST /api/ai/translate-query`):
```json
{
  "user_query": "Show me all FX trades above $1M from last week",
  "conversation_context": [
    { "role": "user", "content": "previous query text" },
    { "role": "assistant", "query": { /* previous generated query */ } }
  ]
}
```
**Headers**: `Authorization: Bearer <TEA_TOKEN>`

**Response**:
```json
{
  "success": true,
  "generated_query": {
    "filters": [...],
    "sort": [...],
    "date_range": {...},
    "pagination": {...}
  },
  "display_message": "Searching for FX trades above $1M from the last 7 days...",
  "clarification_needed": false,
  "clarification_question": null
}
```

This `generated_query` is then sent via the **existing WebSocket** to the trade server using the same format the form-based search currently uses.

### Full Requirements (Phase 2 — MCP Server)

If/when you introduce an MCP server, the server team needs to provide:

| Requirement | Details |
|-------------|---------|
| **MCP Server Process** | A new server process (Node.js, Python, or Java) implementing MCP protocol (JSON-RPC 2.0 over HTTP/SSE) |
| **Tool Definitions** | JSON Schema definitions for each tool: `search_trades`, `get_trade_details`, `get_aggregations`, etc. |
| **Authentication** | MCP server must authenticate TEA tokens |
| **Query Sandboxing** | Read-only access; no mutations. Queries should be parameterized to prevent injection |
| **Response Format** | Standardized JSON response: `{ total_count, page, page_size, trades: [...] }` |
| **Schema Endpoint** | Returns the current trade schema (field names, types, enums) for LLM prompt injection |
| **Pagination Support** | Server-side pagination (offset/limit or cursor-based) for large result sets |
| **Aggregation Support** | Ability to return grouped/aggregated results (e.g., *"Total notional by counterparty"*) |
| **Performance** | Query response time < 500ms for standard searches; < 2s for complex aggregations |

