## 11. Data Security Architecture

> [!CAUTION]
> Since trade data is sensitive, this section defines the strict security boundaries.

### What the LLM Sees vs. What It Never Sees

| ✅ LLM Receives | ❌ LLM NEVER Receives |
|-----------------|----------------------|
| Trade schema (field names, types, enums) | Actual trade records |
| User's natural language query | Counterparty names, trader names |
| Operator definitions and business rules | Trade IDs, notional amounts |
| Previous generated queries (structured JSON) | Any PII or sensitive financial data |
| Current date for relative date resolution | Authentication tokens |

### Security Flow

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph Safe["Sent to Bedrock ✅"]
        S1["Trade schema metadata"]
        S2["User NL query"]
        S3["System prompt"]
        S4["Previous query JSON"]
    end
    
    subgraph Blocked["Never sent to Bedrock ❌"]
        B1["Trade records"]
        B2["TEA tokens"]
        B3["User PII"]
        B4["Counterparty data"]
    end
    
    Safe --> LLM["AWS Bedrock<br/>(Claude)"]
    Blocked -.->|BLOCKED| FW["Backend Proxy<br/>Firewall"]
```

### Additional Security Measures
- **Backend proxy validates** all requests with TEA token before calling Bedrock
- **Bedrock stays within your AWS VPC** — no data leaves your cloud boundary
- **Prompt injection protection** — user input is sanitized and placed within a controlled template
- **Audit logging** — every AI query is logged with user ID, timestamp, and generated output
- **No conversation persistence in LLM** — each Bedrock call is stateless; context is managed server-side

